                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94115 Exchange/7–1944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-19T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 19, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 4:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4606. American Interests—Far East. Foreign Office note July 12 states that
                    contents of Department’s 2189, June 27, forwarded Swiss Minister, Tokyo, who
                    replies he submitted it Japanese Foreign Office. Gorgé adds Japanese Government
                    in usual manner will probably request reciprocity so that it would be of
                    interest inform Japanese Government manner American Government intends to
                    repatriate via Soviet territory Japanese subjects now in the United States.</p>
                <p>In handing above mentioned note to Secretary, Swiss Foreign Office official added
                    that Gorgé reports Japanese did not understand “taking advantage of railroad
                    connections between Japanese-held territory and Soviet territory”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
